 1. Before starting WoR, turn off real-time scanning / real-time protection:
      - Windows Security → Virus & threat protection → Manage settings
      - Turn off Real-time protection
      - If another antivirus is installed, temporarily disable its real-time scanning too.
  2. Run WoR / corrected WoR setup as Administrator.
  3. Select:
      - Target device: correct Raspberry Pi model, for example Pi 4 / Pi 400 ARM64
      - Windows image: Windows ARM64 image
      - Edition: desired Windows edition
      - Target drive: the USB/SSD you want to erase and use
      - Driver package: matching Raspberry Pi Windows ARM64 drivers
      - UEFI package: matching Raspberry Pi UEFI firmware
      - Partition scheme: GPT
      - Image deployer: WIMGAPI, if available
  4. Confirm the target drive carefully.
      - WoR will erase the selected drive.
      - Make sure it is not the internal Windows disk.
  5. Let WoR complete these stages:
      - Create BOOT FAT32 partition
      - Create Windows NTFS partition
      - Apply Windows ARM64 image
      - Inject Raspberry Pi drivers
      - Copy Raspberry Pi boot package / UEFI files
      - Create EFI boot files and BCD boot configuration
  6. Do not remove the USB/SSD until WoR finishes.
  7. After WoR is done, safely eject the drive and try booting it on the Raspberry Pi.

  If WoR Fails Near The End Or Boot Fails

  The fix that worked was to repair only the boot/BCD part instead of repeating the whole Windows image installation.

  1. Reconnect the WoR USB/SSD to the Windows PC.
  2. Keep real-time protection disabled temporarily, because the failure was related to boot/helper files being blocked
     as virus or potentially unwanted software.
  3. Open PowerShell or Terminal as Administrator.
  4. Find the two WoR partitions:
      - BOOT partition: FAT32
      - Windows partition: NTFS
  5. Rebuild the EFI boot files using Microsoft bcdboot:

  bcdboot.exe <WindowsLetter>:\Windows /s <BootLetter>: /f UEFI /offline /c

  Example format only:

  bcdboot.exe W:\Windows /s S: /f UEFI /offline /c

  6. Fix the BCD entries so they point to the Windows partition:

  bcdedit.exe /store <BootLetter>:\EFI\Microsoft\Boot\BCD /set {default} device partition=<WindowsLetter>:
  bcdedit.exe /store <BootLetter>:\EFI\Microsoft\Boot\BCD /set {default} osdevice partition=<WindowsLetter>:
  bcdedit.exe /store <BootLetter>:\EFI\Microsoft\Boot\BCD /set {default} path \Windows\System32\winload.efi
  bcdedit.exe /store <BootLetter>:\EFI\Microsoft\Boot\BCD /set {default} systemroot \Windows
  bcdedit.exe /store <BootLetter>:\EFI\Microsoft\Boot\BCD /set {default} detecthal Yes
  bcdedit.exe /store <BootLetter>:\EFI\Microsoft\Boot\BCD /set {default} testsigning on
  bcdedit.exe /store <BootLetter>:\EFI\Microsoft\Boot\BCD /set {default} nointegritychecks on
  bcdedit.exe /store <BootLetter>:\EFI\Microsoft\Boot\BCD /set {default} recoveryenabled No
  bcdedit.exe /store <BootLetter>:\EFI\Microsoft\Boot\BCD /set {default} bootstatuspolicy IgnoreAllFailures

  7. Make sure this file exists:

  <BootLetter>:\EFI\BOOT\BOOTAA64.EFI

  If missing, copy:

  Copy-Item <BootLetter>:\EFI\Microsoft\Boot\bootmgfw.efi <BootLetter>:\EFI\BOOT\BOOTAA64.EFI -Force

  8. Safely eject the drive and boot again.
  9. If it boots but shows a blank screen, edit config.txt on the BOOT partition and add conservative HDMI settings only
     for display troubleshooting.
     For the WoR Pi 4 / Pi 400 setup, config.txt on the BOOT partition should contain this:
     arm_64bit=1
     arm_boost=1
     enable_uart=1
     uart_2ndstage=1
     enable_gic=1
     armstub=RPI_EFI.fd
     disable_commandline_tags=1
     disable_overscan=1
     device_tree_address=0x3e0000
     device_tree_end=0x400000
     dtoverlay=miniuart-bt
     dtoverlay=upstream-pi4
   
     If boot starts but the screen stays blank, add these lines at the bottom:
   
     hdmi_force_hotplug=1
     hdmi_force_hotplug:0=1
     hdmi_group=2
     hdmi_group:0=2
     hdmi_mode=82
     hdmi_mode:0=82
     config_hdmi_boost=7
   
     So the final working version can be:
   
     arm_64bit=1
     arm_boost=1
     enable_uart=1
     uart_2ndstage=1
     enable_gic=1
     armstub=RPI_EFI.fd
     disable_commandline_tags=1
     disable_overscan=1
     device_tree_address=0x3e0000
     device_tree_end=0x400000
     dtoverlay=miniuart-bt
     dtoverlay=upstream-pi4
   
     hdmi_force_hotplug=1
     hdmi_force_hotplug:0=1
     hdmi_group=2
     hdmi_group:0=2
     hdmi_mode=82
     hdmi_mode:0=82
     config_hdmi_boost=7
